			<tr>
				<td colspan="2" align="left"><div class="postbody">I think, given the history of the Middle East, its caste system, government by exclusion, totalitarian regiemes, etc... that a republic wouldn't be workable.  I also don't think that our concept of a Western democracy would work.  The people of Iraq have no experience with participation in government and the concept isn't historically supported within their culture.  Attempting to give sovereinty to the people would devolve into violence as they try to exclude each other and play for power.
<br />

<br />
How about a federation?  Three provinces with representation in scale to their population.  In order to be included in the economics of the country they would have to participate in the federation.  Hm... problems being the richer province would attempt to dominate the poorer.  Calls for independance perhaps?  Provinces needing to be controlled by a third military party?  Progroms against the minorities within the individual provinces? Calls for vote by economics potential of a region as opposed to population? Gerrymandering by Western interests? 
<br />

<br />
I would tend towards a federation which is overseen by a third party multi-national military.  Not a nice thing but there's a big mess there now and this may be the only way to avoid it getting bigger.  Iraq aka Bosnia 2004?
<br />

<br />
Well, that's wide open.  Have a ball man.<span class="gensmall"></span>


