				<td colspan="2" align="left"><div class="postbody"><a href="http://countrystudies.us/turkey/" target="_blank" class="postlink">Decent history of Turkey</a>.
<br />
<a href="http://www.nationbynation.com/Turkey/Index.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">Very simple stuff</a>.
<br />
<a href="http://ccat.sas.upenn.edu/~rs143/map.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">Some maps of the Ottoman Empire</a> (which was broken up after WW1 to make Turkey and most of the Arab states in the mideast).
<br />
<a href="http://www.ataturk.com/index2.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">Brief history of Ataturk</a>. Failure to understand this guy will prevent you from understanding Turkey. Insulting this guy to a Turk will get you a bloody nose.
<br />

<br />
In short, Turkey is a nation with a very long history, and a desire to be both part of Europe and Asia. The nations in the middle east that are problems arose due to breaking up the Ottoman empire after WW1. Thus creating all those lines in the sand that make folks so exited: Kuwait, Iraq, Jordan, Syria, Palestine, Saudi Arabia. We are still paying the price of World War One. Failure to think things out at that time is why we got WW2 and the current mess in the mideast. Failure to think things out now will only make it continue.
<br />

<br />
The British had a policy of drawing borders to split up large tribes and have competing/warring tribes inside the same borders. This principle (divide and conquer) made it easier to rule by playing one side against each other.
<br />

<br />
My advice would be to sit down at the library at your local college and try to read what you can get your hands on. We jumped into this mess without thinking about it. Slogans and propaganda got us there. Shooting from the hip only works in movies. We are going to be married to it for many decades. The only way out will be from careful thinking and deliberate planning. I do not believe that the folks in the whitehouse are capable of such planning: their religeous beliefs (rapturism) prevent such long term planning.<span class="gensmall"></span>


