###
<br />

<br />
Stryke the anamosity Antonelf presumes is tied to Elbrich's posting history, and the presumption that Canadians have any say in Iraq's reconstruction.  Allies that turn their back on you in time of war, are despised.  This may come as a suprise to some, but you suffer backlash when you fail to fulfil your moral and social obligations.
<br />

<br />
Little things like mutual protection treaties can become real important when the @#%$ hits the fan.  Failure to respect them can have consequences far more dire than prejudice of PoV on Forums.  Chew on that a little.  I cannot claim to know your nationality any more than I could positively know Elbrichs.  You both are flying colors or claiming allegence on these boards to Canada.  You guys get no say. Not without contrition for the negligence to an ally and the negative propaganda after the dogs of war had been unleashed.
<br />

<br />
Getting so closely involved in other people internal politics is like getting involved in another family's relationships.  Yeah you may know your neighbors really well... maybe not.  But none the less, no matter how close, there are lines at which you do not cross in getting involved in their household matters.
<br />

<br />
That line in international relations is even FARTHER back.  We do not have a homogenous one world government.  Thank all that is good and free for that.  We do not want one. You do not want one.  The Iraqis sure as heck don't want one. If the insult goes too far or if there is a threat to a nation, it has the right to defend itself regardless of the largely compassionate concerns of the UN at large.
<br />

<br />
Publicly spouting anti war rhetoric during an active war is uncouth.  You do it to your enemies.  Your allies you deal with in a manner that shows respect for your relationship.  Failing to approach your ally with tact at such times, regardless of the strength of your point of view, is likely to leave lasting impressions.
<br />

<br />
Here are some suggestions:
<br />

<br />
When stepping over the line, acknowlege the line.  Call the boundries of your discussion and acknowlege your right or lack there of to speak with authority.
<br />

<br />
Argue in the abstract.  It really is a principle you are trying to communicate anyway.  Argue the principle and avoid the specific when the specific is none of your business.
<br />

<br />
If there is a disparity in your view of where the line or authority is: Argue that first.
<br />

<br />
###
<br />

<br />
Tang,
<br />

<br />
You are quite right about Turkey being the model of republic democracy in the Middle East.  It has not been the best of examples of what happens. But by other regional examples its pretty civilized by European standards.  We will forget about the ethnic cleansing of Armenians and Kurds.  Everyone overthere is doing it after all...
<br />

<br />
I wont pick on them too much.  They are evil by my personal standards. I acknowlege them as an ally though and I only have rights granted by my membership in humanity to decry foul at the wholesale murder of civilians to suppress rebellion.
<br />

<br />
Here is another good illustration of the Ottoman (Turk) empire. One extended arab family that ruled Turkey, Iraq, the Saudi, the Holy lands, North Africa, Greece, Armenia, and pushed up into the Germanic and Slavic territories and ruled all of Egypt. Follow the link and click the 1683 button then run up and down the timeline.
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://i-cias.com/e.o/atlas/ottomans.htm" target="_blank">http://i-cias.com/e.o/atlas/ottomans.htm</a>
<br />

<br />
The maps of Islam I think are a little out of place.  This is not the US against islam.  This is the US cleaning up a dangerous problem about to explode from the release of cold war pressure.
<br />

<br />
Hussein was not a muslim.  To be muslim you have to follow the will of God as a pattern of life.  That is why the arab and islamic world is not rising up.  Hussein is no martyr he is evil by any civilized standard.  The US does not want to stay in Iraq.  We want the country stable and not making threatening postures.
<br />

<br />
Osama may be a muslim.  But he's a kooky one.  The fanatics are by no means a majority in the world of Islamic Faith.  No more than Jim Jones is representitive of Christian ethic.  The world of islam is not rising up in defence of him either.  By historic record human beings are all living better lives than they wer under the rule of people like him.  Only the direly dissaffected are drawn to such organizations.
<br />

<br />
What ever the Iraqi people want is their business.  It is not ours to call the shots for them except to garantee their reconstruction and stability as mandated by multi-national treaty and to ensure our own safety and security of foreign assets as is mandated by basic self preservation.
<br />

<br />
I do not think that a ethnic republic would work in Iraq any better than it did in Yugoslavia.  The threat of violence against the US and other atrocities internally were all based on cetralized power of one clan over others.  I think its time that they learned to intermingle and tolerate each other.  Not sit across borders and eye each others oil.
<br />

<br />
The wealth of the region makes it far more volitile than Yugoslavia or Turkey.  Lines should be drawn to Jerry Mander the ethnic differences and make them have to work together.  I dont know if there anough forward thinking Iraqi governing council guys to make that happen.  I think an ethnic republic is the most likely outcome.  I just dont think that it is the best option.
<br />

<br />
Its not divide and conquer... its unify for peace.  It was not divide and conquer after WW1 either. The area was already conquered. Just as it is now.  It's the old bastard is gone, try to make better choices
<br />

<br />
Turkey would pacify naturally under the release of pressure.  Imagine a world where Kurds from Turkey could freely travel to Iraq without fear of bandits and border Guards.  Imagine if the pressure release had enough of an affect on Iran to realize it can be a theocracy and not be threatened.  Where Shia could travel from Tehran to Basra to Cairo into Jerusalem and Istanbul and every holy shrine inbetween without machinegun or landmine threatening your trip.
<br />

<br />
It doesnt require military occupation, it requires tolerance to achieve.  Tolerance is a trait that takes a while to set in.  I think that a ethnic republic will be the first form of government tried.  I think it would be in everyones best interest if they sought to make a democratic republic with the ethic groups divideed fairly evenly.  They really need to approach things from a "how can we get along together" perspective for long term stability.
<br />

<br />
Its not my call though... It's the iraqi's.<span class="gensmall"></span>


