				<td colspan="2" align="left"><div class="postbody">Not gonna get into it with you, Poppa, but you've got a pretty black-and-white view of what went on back then.
<br />

<br />
I'm not going to talk about France, Germany, and Russia, because they appear to have had a lot to lose by this invasion.
<br />

<br />
I will address Canada, however, because either your press presented a biased viewpoint or you've forgotten some key facts. Canada did not turn its back on anybody, but they did push for more (or any) evidence to justify an invasion of Iraq, a request that seems pretty logical. When that wasn't forthcoming, they said "okay, we'll help, but with the blessing of our other allies in the UN". You conveniently forget that we have been first in line to help our ally in the past, and have troops in Afghanistan as we speak. Canada is helping its ally, and at no time has it turned its back on the United States.
<br />

<br />
In fact, Canada even tried to broker a compromise between the U.S. and the U.N., in an attempt to make everybody come out a winner, a compromise that really only amounted to postponing the whole thing while the inspectors finished up. I'm not saying the compromise would have worked, but it shows a clear desire to keep everybody working together, which in my books is a good thing. There was a concerted effort by the Canadian government to make the whole thing work, but the U.S. went in anyway, on the incorrect assumption that the Iraqis were poised to nuke the western world into oblivion.
<br />

<br />
When the dust had settled, Canada <span style="font-style: italic">still</span> pledged 300 million dollars towards reconstruction, because our ally needed help. Not much on the surface, but per-capita that would be equivalent to 4 billion coming from a country the size of the U.S.
<br />

<br />
So "despise" (LOL!) the country all you want, but acknowledge its contributions when you do.<span class="gensmall"></span>


